# UNIT II: BUILDING IMAGES & MANAGING CONTAINERS
## WEEK 3: Dockerfile Essentials & Custom Image Creation

---

### A. Dockerfile Basics
A **Dockerfile** is a plain-text script that defines how to assemble an image, one layer at a time.

**Key instructions:**

- `FROM` — Sets the base image (must be the first instruction)
- `RUN` — Runs a command at build time (produces a new layer)
- `COPY` — Transfers files from the build context into the image
- `ADD` — Similar to COPY but also extracts tar archives and supports URLs
- `WORKDIR` — Defines the working directory inside the container
- `ENV` — Sets environment variables
- `EXPOSE` — Documents which port the app listens on (does not publish it)
- `VOLUME` — Declares a mount point for external storage
- `CMD` — Specifies the default command (can be overridden at runtime)
- `ENTRYPOINT` — Defines the primary executable (not easily overridden)

---

### B. Build Context & .dockerignore
The **build context** includes everything in the directory sent to the Docker daemon when running `docker build`.

Use `.dockerignore` to keep unnecessary files out:
```
node_modules
.git
*.md
.env
```

A smaller build context means faster image builds.

